Comprehensive master list of course topics

Track 1: Process Measurement and Analysis
Focus: Engineering, applying, and mastering the selection of field devices for complex process media.
1.1 Principles of Pressure Measurement: Application, Engineering, and Selection
1.2 Level Measurement Technologies and Selection (including but not limited to DP, Guided Wave Radar, Nucleonic, and Ultrasonic)
1.3 Flow Measurement Engineering and Selection (including but not limited to DP, Coriolis, Ultrasonic, Magnetic, and Multi-Phase Flow Meters - MPFM)
1.4 Temperature Sensing and Selection (including RTDs, Thermocouples, Thermowells, and Wake Frequency Calculations)
1.5 Online Process Analyzers Selection and Application (including but not limited to Gas Chromatography, Spectrometry, and CEMS)
1.6 Liquid Analytical Instrumentation Selection (including pH, Conductivity, Dissolved Oxygen, and more)
1.7 Instrument Calibration, Metrology, and Smart Field Device Diagnostics
1.8 Hazardous Area Classifications and Intrinsically Safe / Explosion-Proof Equipment Selection
Track 2: Process Control and Final Elements
Focus: Manipulating the process safely, efficiently, and effectively.
2.1 Process Dynamics and Practical PID Controller Tuning
2.2 Control Valve Sizing, Selection, and Noise/Cavitation Mitigation
2.3 Advanced Regulatory Control: Cascade, Feedforward, Ratio, and Split-Range
2.4 Control Valve Actuators (Pneumatic, Hydraulic, Electric) and Smart Digital Positioners Selection
2.5 Introduction to Multivariable Control and Model Predictive Control (MPC)
2.6 Relief Valves, Rupture Disks, and Mechanical Overpressure Protection Selection
Track 3: Equipment and Package Instrumentation & Control
Focus: Dedicated control strategies for major mechanical and process packages.
3.1 Rotating Equipment Control: Pump Protection, Instrumentation, and Interlocks
3.2 Compressor Control Systems: Centrifugal/Reciprocating Instrumentation and Anti-Surge Control
3.3 Separation Package Instrumentation and Control: 2-Phase and 3-Phase Separators
3.4 Desalter Instrumentation, Control Loops, and Interface Measurement Selection
3.5 Fired Heater and Boiler Control Systems: Combustion, Drum Level, and Burner Management Systems (BMS)
Track 4: Fire & Gas Detection and Protection Systems
Focus: Designing, selecting, and engineering critical life and asset protection systems.
4.1 Fire & Gas Philosophy, Risk Assessment, and Detector Performance Mapping
4.2 Toxic and Combustible Gas Detectors: Engineering, Placement, and Technology Selection
4.3 Flame and Heat Detectors: Engineering, Placement, and Technology Selection
4.4 F&G Logic Solvers, Alarm Systems, and Integration with Plant ESD Systems
4.5 F&G System Deliverables, Maintenance, and Calibration Strategies
Track 5: Digital Networks, Power, and System Integration
Focus: The nervous system of the plant—architecture, power, logic, and human interfaces.
5.1 Architecture of Control Systems: PLCs, DCS, and SCADA
5.2 Instrumentation and Control Systems Power Supply, UPS, and Power Distribution Networks
5.3 Industrial Communication Protocols (including but not limited to Modbus, HART, and Profibus)
5.4 Advanced Field Networks: Foundation Fieldbus, Ethernet/IP, and WirelessHART
5.5 Alarm Management Strategies and Rationalization (ISA-18.2)
5.6 High-Performance HMI / GUI Design Principles for Operator Effectiveness
5.7 Cybersecurity for Industrial Control Systems (ICS/OT Security)
Track 6: Engineering Deliverables and Project Execution
Focus: Generating the core documentation and executing projects according to global gate systems.
6.1 Projects’ Decision Support Package (DSP) Development according to Project Gate System (PGS)
6.2 Instrumentation and Process Control Deliverables: Development and Review of P&IDs
6.3 Detailed Engineering Deliverables: Cause & Effect (C&E) Matrices, Loop Drawings, and Wiring Diagrams
6.4 Instrument Index, I/O Lists, and Datasheet Development and Review
Track 7: Functional Safety - The Device Level (Source: IEC 61508)
Focus: Understanding the foundational reliability engineering behind safety equipment.
7.1 The IEC 61508 Framework: The Foundation of Functional Safety
7.2 Hardware Fault Tolerance (HFT) and Safe Failure Fractions (SFF)
7.3 Reliability Engineering Basics: Failure Rates, MTBF, and MTTF
7.4 FMEDA in Smart Devices and Device Selection Strategies for Safety Services
7.5 Device Certification vs. "Prior Use" / "Proven in Use" Justifications
Track 8: Process Industry Safety Lifecycle (Source: IEC 61511)
Focus: Executing safety engineering from concept to decommissioning.
8.1 The IEC 61511 Safety Lifecycle Phase by Phase
8.2 Hazard & Risk Assessment: Transitioning from HAZOP to LOPA
8.3 Developing a Robust Safety Requirements Specification (SRS)
8.4 SIF Design and Selection: Voting Architectures, Common Cause Failures (β-factor), and Diversity
8.5 SIL Verification: PFDavg​ Calculations and Target SIL Achievement
8.6 Operations, Maintenance, Proof Testing Design, and Partial Stroke Testing (PST)
8.7 Management of Change (MOC) and Decommissioning Safety Systems
Track 9: Advanced Engineering Masterclasses
Focus: Bridging theory and the reality of plant operations and brownfield challenges.
9.1 BPCS vs. SIS: The Criticality of Independence, Separation, and Shared Components
9.2 Overcoming "Paper Safety": Real-World Pitfalls in SIL Realization and Field Installations
9.3 Revamping and Migrating Legacy Control and Safety Systems in Brownfield Sites


Track 10: Artificial Intelligence in Instrumentation, Control, and Safety
Focus: Deploying Machine Learning and AI in Operational Technology (OT) to optimize performance, enhance safety, and predict failures without compromising plant stability.
10.1 Foundations of Industrial AI: Demystifying Machine Learning, Deep Learning, and Edge AI for Control Engineers
10.2 AI-Empowered Predictive Maintenance (PdM) and Asset Health Monitoring: Moving Beyond Condition-Based Maintenance for Valves, Pumps, and Compressors
10.3 Next-Generation Pipeline Leak Detection Systems (PLDS): Leveraging AI for Acoustic, Fiber Optic, and Computational Pipeline Monitoring (CPM) False Alarm Reduction
10.4 Plant Operation and Advanced Process Control (APC) Leveraging AI: Neural Networks for Non-Linear Control and Soft Sensors (Inferential Measurement)
10.5 Power Optimization and Energy Management: AI-Driven Load Shedding, Compressor Load Balancing, and Fired Heater Efficiency Tuning
10.6 Computer Vision in Operational Technology: AI for Thermal Leak Detection, Flare Optimization, and Automated Gauge/Dial Reading
10.7 AI in Alarm Management (ISA-18.2): Dynamic Alarm Rationalization, Flood Suppression, and Root Cause Analysis during Plant Upsets
10.8 AI and Functional Safety (IEC 61508/61511): The Challenges of Determinism, Evaluating AI/ML Reliability, and Dynamic Risk Assessment
10.9 Generative AI and Large Language Models (LLMs) in Engineering: Automating P&ID Reviews, SRS Generation, and Troubleshooting from O&M Manuals
10.10 Edge vs. Cloud AI Architectures in ICS: Navigating Latency, OT Cybersecurity, and Integrating AI with Existing DCS/SCADA Systems

